>place to start
Bingo.
You can write a few scenes without an outline, but at some point it gets harder to pants a story without it. How much detail is in your outline is different each time.
Using my current project as an example, I have a sentence fragment for each major scene. That becomes a written out plot guide, one or two sentences per major scene. In this case I also have a second summary of the setting. As I introduce major characters (directly or indirectly) I write up a character entry.

It's not as though I want a finished outline before starting. It's a growing framework and guide until I reach the end of the first draft. Sometimes it moves in advance of the story, other times I pants for a few evening and then update the outline.
